      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How are indirect factory overheads absorbed into the cost of a product?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Pool the indirect factory costs, then apply them using a rate such as machine hours or labour hours. Factory overheads of Rs 12 lakh spread over 24,000 machine hours give a rate of Rs 50 an hour, so a job using 30 machine hours absorbs Rs 1,500. Fixed overheads are absorbed on normal capacity, not actual low output."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between direct expenses and indirect factory overheads?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Direct expenses can be traced to a single unit or job, such as raw material, job work charges and machine hire taken for one order, while indirect factory overheads cannot, such as factory rent, supervisor salary, shed power and maintenance. Direct costs move with output; indirect overheads largely do not, which is why they need an absorption rate."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Are factory overheads included in closing stock valuation under AS 2?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. AS 2 requires cost of conversion, including a systematic allocation of fixed and variable production overheads, to be included in finished goods and work in progress. Fixed overheads are allocated on normal capacity. Selling, distribution and general administration costs stay out. Stock is then carried at the lower of that cost and net realisable value."
          }
        }
      ]
